nings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Braham","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from Braham in Spofforth (Yorkshire) or Brantham in Suffolk (recorded as <i>Braham</i> in 1198). Braham in Yorkshire was probably named with the Old English personal name <i>Brahha</i> + <i>hām</i> ‘homestead’. Brantham in Suffolk means ‘the steep homestead’, from Old English <i>brant</i> ‘steep’ + <i>hām</i>.","Irish and Scottish: shortened form of Gaelic <b>Mac an Bhreitheamhan</b> ‘son of the judge’. Compare   Brain  .","Jewish: shortened form of   Abraham  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Brain","meanings":["English: apparently a nickname from Middle English <i>brain</i> ‘brain, mind’, probably short for <i>brainwod</i> ‘mad in the mind, furious’. Compare   Brainard  .","Irish (Down) and Scottish: shortened Anglicized form of Irish <b>Mac an Bhreitheamhan</b>, Scottish Gaelic <b>Mac a' Bhreitheamhan</b> ‘son of the judge’, from <i>breitheamh</i> ‘judge’. Compare   Braham   2."]},{"name":"Bream","meanings":["English:","nickname for a fierce or energetic person, from Middle English <i>brem(e)</i>, <i>brim(me)</i> ‘fierce, vigorous’ (from Old English <i>brēme</i> ‘famous, noble’), or from a Middle English form of the Old English personal name <i>Brēme</i> with the same meaning.","variant of   Braham  ."]},{"name":"Brame","meanings":["English (Suffolk and Norfolk): variant of   Braham  .","German (also <b>Bräme</b>): variant of   Brahm   2. The surnames <i>Brame</i> and <i>Bräme</i> are very rare in Germany.","French: nickname from Old Occitan <i>brame</i> ‘cry, howl’."]}]},{"name":"Joan","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Contracted form of Old French <i>Jo(h)anne</i>, from Latin <i>Io(h)anna</i> (  see  Joanna  ). In England this was the usual feminine form of   John   from the Middle English period onwards and was extremely popular, but in the 16th and 17th centuries it steadily lost ground to   Jane .  It was strongly revived in the first part of the 20th century, partly under the influence of  George Bernard Shaw's  play St Joan (  1923 ), based on the life of  Joan of Arc  (  1412–31 ). Claiming to be guided by the voices of the saints, she persuaded the French dauphin to defy the occupying English forces and have himself crowned, and she led the French army that raised the siege of Orleans in  1429 . The following year she was captured by the Burgundians and sold to the English, and a year later she was burned at the stake for witchcraft at the age of 18 or 19. Her story has captured the imagination of many writers, and she is variously portrayed as a national and political hero, a model of apolitical straightforwardness and honesty, and a religious heroine. She was canonized in  1920 . More recent influences have included the American film actress  Joan Crawford  (  1908–77 , born  Lucille le Sueur ), the British actress  Joan Collins  (  b. 1933 ), the American comedienne  Joan Rivers  (  b. 1933 ), and the West Indian pop singer  Joan Armatrading  (  b. 1950 )."],"variants":[{"name":"John","meanings":["As a boy's name this represents a revival of Middle English <i>Jan</i>, a by‐form of   John  , or an adoption of the common European form with this spelling. As a girl's name it is a short form of names such as   Janet   and   Janice ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Mrs. Joan De Braham was born about 1355, in Chippenham, Wiltshire, England, United Kingdom. She had at least 2 daughters with John de Braham Jr. She died in 1432, in Brome, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 78."},"et":{"Abt 1355–1432":"umbes 1355–1432","1350–1420":"1350–1420","1343–1408":"1343–1408","1370–Female":"1370–Surnud","1355–1432":"1355–1432","about 1370":"umbes 1370","BEF 1408":"enne 1408","Abt 1355":"umbes 1355","1432":"1432","1355":"1355","1420":"1420","1343":"1343","1350":"1350","1370":"1370","1408":"1408","Brome, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom":"Brome, Suffolk, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Brome, Suffolk, England":"Brome, Suffolk, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Chippenham, Wiltshire, England, United Kingdom":"Chippenham, Wiltshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"Abt 1355–1432":"noin 1355–1432","1350–1420":"1350–1420","1343–1408":"1343–1408","1370–Female":"1370–Kuollut","1355–1432":"1355–1432","about 1370":"noin 1370","BEF 1408":"ennen vuotta 1408","Abt 1355":"noin 1355","1432":"1432","1355":"1355","1420":"1420","1343":"1343","1350":"1350","1370":"1370","1408":"1408","Brome, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom":"Brome, Suffolk, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Brome, Suffolk, England":"Brome, Suffolk, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Chippenham, Wiltshire, England, United Kingdom":"Chippenham, Wiltshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"Abt 1355–1432":"environ 1355–1432","1350–1420":"1350–1420","1343–1408":"1343–1408","1370–Female":"1370–Décédée","1355–1432":"1355–1432","about 1370":"environ 1370","BEF 1408":"avant 1408","Abt 1355":"environ 1355","1432":"1432","1355":"1355","1420":"1420","1343":"1343","1350":"1350","1370":"1370","1408":"1408","Brome, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom":"Brome, Suffolk, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","Brome, Suffolk, England":"Brome, Suffolk, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","Chippenham, Wiltshire, England, United Kingdom":"Chippenham, Wiltshire, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","lifeSummary":"Mrs. Joan De Braham est née environ 1355, à Chippenham, Wiltshire, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni. Elle a eu au moins 2 filles avec John de Braham Jr. Elle est décédée en 1432, à Brome, Suffolk, A